{"title_page": "St Andrew's Church, West Tarring", "text_new": "{{For|the other church in the Borough of Worthing dedicated to St Andrew|St Andrew's Church, Worthing}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox church\n|name                 = St Andrew's Church\n|image                = St Andrew's Church, West Tarring, Worthing.jpg\n|caption              = The church from the northwest\n|location             = Church Road, West Tarring, Worthing, West Sussex BN13 1HQ\n|country              = England\n|coordinates          = {{Coord|50.8247|-0.3958|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n|denomination         = [[Church of England]]\n|website              = [http://www.tarring.org.uk/st-andrews-west-tarring.org.uk/index.htm Saint Andrew's Parish Church, West Tarring]\n|founded date         = 11th century\n|founder              = [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]\n|dedication           = [[Saint Andrew]]\n|dedicated date       = By 1372\n|consecrated date     =\n|status               = [[Church of England parish church|Parish church]]\n|functional status    = Active\n|heritage designation = [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade II*]]\n|designated date      = 11 October 1949\n|architect            =\n|style                = [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]]\n|groundbreaking       =\n|completed date       =\n|construction cost    =\n|capacity             =\n|parish               = West Tarring, St Andrew\n|deanery              = [[Rural Deanery of Worthing]]\n|archdeaconry         = [[Archdeaconry of Chichester|Chichester]]\n|diocese              = [[Diocese of Chichester|Chichester]]\n|province             = [[Province of Canterbury|Canterbury]]\n|rector               = Rev. Mark Lyon\n}}\n\n'''St Andrew's Church''' is the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Tarring, West Sussex]], [[England]]. Founded in the 11th century in a then rural parish which had earlier been granted to the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], the church remained a [[Royal Peculiar|peculier of Canterbury]] <!-- (sic) !--> for many centuries thereafter. It served nearby parishes when their churches fell into disrepair, [[John Selden]] was baptised here, and the church became a base for [[smuggling]]. The present building is mostly 13th-century, and its tall spire is a landmark in the area.<ref name=WAPH168>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1977|loc=\u00a7168.}}</ref> The church is a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade II* Listed Building]].\n\n==History==\nThe parish of West Tarring is now part of the Borough of Worthing, but has ancient origins as a [[South Downs]] [[strip parish]] of about {{convert|1200|acre|0}}.<ref name=VCH18267>{{harvnb|Salzman|1980|pp=270\u2013280.}}</ref>  It ran for about {{convert|3|mi|0}} from its northern extremity at Bost Hill, on the track to [[Findon, West Sussex|Findon]] (now the [[A24 road (England)|A24 road]]), to the [[English Channel]] coast in the south, and was much narrower apart from a thin strip of land extending westwards.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies12>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=12.}}</ref><ref name=DaviesFig3>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|loc=Fig. 3.}}</ref> Many coastal parishes in Sussex were this shape: many different soils and varieties of land would be included within the boundaries, from chalky downland in the north to marshy grassland near the coast.<ref name=Davies12/> Two settlements developed, of which West Tarring was the larger and more central. (The name \"Tarring\" was, and still is, also used, but the \"West\" prefix was often used to prevent confusion with [[Tarring Neville]] near [[Lewes]].)<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies5>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=5.}}</ref> [[Salvington]], the other settlement in the parish, is high on the slopes of the South Downs.<ref name=Davies12/>\n\nThe first documented description of West Tarring was in about AD 939, when [[Athelstan of England|King Athelstan]] granted the [[Manorialism|manor]] of Tarring to [[Canterbury Cathedral|Christ Church]] in [[Canterbury]] (now Canterbury Cathedral).<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies1>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=1.}}</ref> At the time of the [[Domesday Book]] in 1086 it was still held by the [[Archbishop of Canterbury|archbishop]] and had 41 inhabitants. A church is known to have existed at that time;<ref name=VCH18267/> it is likely to have been a wooden building.<ref name=Davies149>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=149.}}</ref>\n\nThe present [[flint]] and stone building<ref name=IoE302248>{{NHLE |num= 1354775 |desc=West Tarring Church (St Andrew's), Church Road (south side), Worthing, Worthing, West Sussex |year=2007 |accessdate=27 September 2009}}</ref> began to take shape in the mid-13th century.<ref name=Davies150>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=150.}}</ref> At that time, the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]], Simon of Tarring, provided sanctuary for [[Richard of Chichester|Richard of Wych (later St Richard of Chichester)]], the new [[Bishop of Chichester]].  He had been barred from his own palace there by [[Henry III of England|King Henry III]], who had been angered by the election of Richard as bishop in place of [[Robert Passelewe]].  While he was based at the church, Richard travelled throughout Sussex, taking services and reputedly performing miracles; he was [[Canonization|canonised]] in 1262.<ref name=Davies150/>\n\nThe dedication to [[Saint Andrew]] was first mentioned in 1372.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=MEWH48>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1998|p=48.}}</ref> In the 15th century the [[chancel]] and tower were rebuilt,<ref name=IoE302248/> apparently under the influence of Canterbury.<ref name=Nairn>{{Harvnb|Nairn|Pevsner|1965|pp=392\u2013393.}}</ref>  The [[rood screen]] also dates from that time.<ref name=VCH18267/> The church only had modest wealth \u2014 its internal fittings were valued at [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]6.13[[Shilling|s]].4[[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|d]]. (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|6.67|1561|r=-1}}}} as of {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} in 1561<ref name=\"Davies151\u2013152\">{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|pp=151\u2013152.}}</ref> \u2014 and unusual fundraising activities were popular.<ref name=VCH18267/> [[Parish Ale|Church ales]] \u2014 drinking sessions held in the church, at which the [[churchwarden]]s sold beer to raise funds for its upkeep \u2014 were popular throughout the 16th century,<ref name=VCH18267/> and often proved to be uproarious occasions at which large quantities of luxurious food were eaten and various entertainers performed.<ref name=Davies153>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=153.}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Organ (music)|organ]] was installed in the late 16th century.<ref name=Davies153/> Bells were hung in the tower by 1518, and there were five in 1533. These had been cast at the Tapsel (or Topsell) family's bell foundry near the church; the Tapsels cast many bells in West Tarring, for churches across Sussex, for about 200 years, and also invented the [[Tapsel gate]] used in some Sussex churchyards.<ref name=Davies155>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=155.}}</ref><ref name=SCM24>{{Cite journal |last=Roberts |first=William J. |year=1950 |title=Tapsel: his gate |journal=Sussex County Magazine |publisher=T.R. Beckett |location=Eastbourne |volume=24 |page=497 |url= http://scm.pastfinders.org/scm_24_tapsel.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070427215629/http://scm.pastfinders.org/scm_24_tapsel.htm |archivedate=27 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe nearby parishes of [[Durrington, West Sussex|Durrington]] and [[Heene]] had been linked to West Tarring since the [[Middle Ages]]. Their [[tithe]]s were combined, and they were administered for ecclesiastical purposes by the incumbents of St Andrew's:<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies149/> for example, burials and baptisms were carried out at West Tarring.<ref name=VCH18220>{{harvnb|Salzman|1980|pp=81\u201385}}</ref><ref name=VCH18221>{{harvnb|Salzman|1980|pp=85\u201392}}</ref> By the 17th century, in common with many churches in the area, Durrington and Heene's churches had declined and fallen into ruin. By 1680 both were in such poor condition that their parishioners were allowed to travel to worship at St Andrew's instead, and services were no longer held at Durrington or Heene.<ref name=VCH18220/><ref name=VCH18221/><ref name=\"Hare28\u201329\">{{Harvnb|Hare|1991|pp=28\u201329.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lychgate at St Andrew's Church, West Tarring.jpg|thumb|right|The early 20th-century lychgate, with the spire of the church behind]]\nMajor changes were made in the mid-19th century. In 1845 the church ceased to be a peculier of Canterbury and instead was placed under the [[Diocese of Chichester]], in conformity with other Church of England churches in the area.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=MEWH48/> In 1853 the vicar instigated a [[Victorian restoration|restoration]] of the church, raising most of the \u00a32,200 (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|2200|1853|r=-2}}}} as of {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} himself.<ref name=Davies157>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=157.}}</ref> Changes included the removal of the timber [[West gallery music|west gallery]],{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} the addition of a vestry, the stripping of previous interior alterations and a complete overhaul of the interior (although certain fittings were retained and reinstalled),<ref name=MEWH48/> and the replacement of the organ.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies157/> Also in 1853 Charles and George Mears<ref>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=West+Tarring&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=WEST+TARRI |title=West Tarring S Andrew |last=Rix |first=Geoff |date=10 November 2006 |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> of the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] recast four of the bells into a new [[Change ringing|ring]] of six.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies156>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=156.}}</ref> The restoration took seven months and was completed in time for [[Holy Week#Holy Week in Protestant churches|Holy Week]] 1854.<ref name=Davies157/> In 1885 [[mosaic]]s designed by the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival architect]] [[William Butterfield]] were installed by Italian craftsmen in the aisles and around the tower arch.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/><ref name=Davies160>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=160.}}</ref>  The church roof partly collapsed around the same time and had to be repaired.<ref name=Davies160/> In the 20th century a [[lychgate]] was erected at the churchyard entrance, the [[reredos]] was replaced, the organ was replaced again, the roof of the chancel was renewed and some [[stained glass]] was added.<ref name=Davies160/><ref name=Davies159>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=159.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Baptismal font|font]] was replaced with a [[Victorian era|Victorian]] one: the main section of its medieval predecessor was removed and taken to Australia by the [[Henty brothers|Henty family]] when they emigrated.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies160/> The Hentys were successful farmers, especially of [[merino sheep]], and lived in one of West Tarring's largest houses. Thomas Henty, the patriarch, sent three of his sons and 150 sheep to [[Western Australia]] in 1829. Eventually the whole family moved to Australia: the pioneers settled in [[Tasmania]], while [[Edward Henty]], another son, became the first settler in [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] and was instrumental in developing the sheep-rearing industry there.<ref name=\"Davies143\u2013145\">{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|pp=143\u2013145.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1977|loc=\u00a7166.}}</ref> They gave the font they had taken with them to a cathedral in Melbourne, which some sources state is [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Melbourne]]<ref name=Davies160/> while the Sussex Parish Churches website states this was at [[St Paul's Cathedral, Melbourne]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sussexparishchurches.org/content/view/594/33/ |title=Worthing \u2013 St Andrew, West Tarring |work=Sussex Parish Churches |date= |accessdate=}}</ref> the architect of which, [[William Butterfield]] had previously worked at St Andrew's Church.\n\n[[Smuggling]] was popular in the Worthing area between the early 18th and early 19th centuries \u2014 sometimes out of necessity, such as during a period of economic hardship in the 1820s which caused the developing town to stagnate.<ref name=Hare100>{{Harvnb|Hare|1991|p=100.}}</ref> One of the leading smugglers at that time, William Cowerson, was employed at St Andrew's Church on restoration work; he regularly used the [[Tomb|table tombs]] in the churchyard to store smuggled alcohol and other contraband.<ref name=Hare101>{{Harvnb|Hare|1991|p=101.}}</ref><ref name=Davies19>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=19.}}</ref>\n\n==Building==\nSt Andrew's Church is an [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] building with some [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] elements.<ref name=WAPH168/><ref name=IoE302248/>  It is a [[Knapping|knapped flint]] structure with stone dressings,<ref name=IoE302248/> and is relatively large in comparison with others in the area\u2014probably because of the influence of Canterbury.<ref name=MEWH48/><ref name=Nairn/>\n\nThe [[nave]] survives in its entirety from the 13th century. It has five [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] with aisles, a [[clerestory]], a vestry on the south side and porches on the north and south sides. The aisles and clerestory have [[lancet window]]s, and the whole composition is in the Early English style.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> The chancel and tower were rebuilt in the 15th century in the Perpendicular style, and the tall octagonal [[Roof shingle|shingled]] spire was added in the 16th century. The chancel has  Perpendicular-style windows with two lights; some of the tower windows more closely resemble the earlier [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] style.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> The east window of the chancel is more ornate than usual: paired shorter lights flank a much taller central light which is surrounded at the top by sexfoils ([[hexafoil|six-lobed]] circular openings).<ref name=Nairn/> The tower and chancel have [[buttress]]es with quoins and dressings of [[ashlar]].<ref name=IoE302248/> The tower also has an interior stair-turret in one corner.<ref name=VCH18267/> Its west door, in the Perpendicular style with a [[hood mould]], is not original: it was inserted in the late 15th century. The windows above it have elaborate [[tracery]].<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> Paul Chapman of [[Hove]]-based [[stained glass]] designers [[Cox & Barnard]] made windows for the west ends of the north and south aisles. They were installed in 1958 and depict [[Thomas Becket|Saint Thomas of Canterbury]] and [[Richard of Chichester|Saint Richard of Chichester]] respectively.<ref name=SGR-22345>{{cite web |url= http://www.stainedglassrecords.org.uk/Ch.asp?ChId=22345 |title=Stained Glass Windows at St. Andrew, Tarring, Sussex |last=Eberhard |first=Robert |date=September 2011 |work=Stained Glass Records website |publisher=Robert Eberhard |accessdate=25 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nInside, there are five pointed arches on each side of the nave, with round columns topped by [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]]. The mosaic decoration, depicting the [[Apostle (Christian)|Twelve Apostles]], runs between and above them, and extends to the tower arch with its octagonal columns.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> The chancel arch was restored in the mid-19th century, but the 15th-century chancel screen was retained during the renovations of 1853. Also in the chancel are six [[misericord]]s, two with carved heads.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=MEWH48/><ref name=Nairn/><ref name=Davies159/>\n\nThere are several memorials in the church. The Henty family is commemorated by a tablet and a 19th-century window near the altar;<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies160/> there is also a window for [[Robert Southey]], the poet, who was the father-in-law of the vicar (Reverend J. Warter) who had restored the church in the mid-19th century.<ref name=Davies160/> The most famous man associated with St Andrew's Church, [[John Selden]],<ref name=Davies61>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=61.}}</ref> was baptised here in 1584<ref name=WAPH168/><ref name=MEWH25>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1998|p=25.}}</ref> and has a memorial and a plaque.<ref name=MEWH48/>\n\n==The church today==\nSt Andrew's Parish Church has been a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade II* Listed Building]] since 11 October 1949.<ref name=IoE302248/> Such buildings are defined as being \"particularly important\" and \"of more than special interest\".<ref name=EH2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/caring/listing/listed-buildings/ |title=Listed Buildings |year=2010 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |access-date=26 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DEarkz4v?url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/caring/listing/listed-buildings/ |archive-date=27 December 2012 |df= }}</ref> As of February 2001 it was one of eight Grade II* listed buildings in the borough of Worthing.<ref name=IoEStats-WSx>{{Cite web|title=Images of England \u2014 Statistics by County (West Sussex) |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/StatisticsPage/default.aspx?StatsCounty=WEST%20SUSSEX |work=[[Images of England]] |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |year=2007 |access-date=2 January 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DNVqdtdK?url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/StatisticsPage/default.aspx?StatsCounty=WEST%20SUSSEX |archive-date=2 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nToday the ecclesiastical [http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parish.php?p=10/142 parish] is smaller than the ancient parish, but the northern part up to Salvington is retained. The other boundaries are the [[West Coastway Line|railway line]] to the south, The Boulevard in the west and a line west of Loxwood Avenue to the east.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parish.php?p=10/142|title=West Tarring Parish Church of S. Andrew |year=2009 |work=A Church Near You |publisher=[[Church of England]] |author=[[Archbishops' Council]] |accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places of worship in Worthing]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Davies |first=Roger |title=Tarring: a Walk Through its History |publisher=Roger W. Davies |location=Tarring |year=1990 |isbn=0-9516309-0-3}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Elleray |first=D. Robert |title=Worthing: a Pictorial History |publisher=Phillimore & Co. |location=Chichester |year=1977 |isbn=0-85033-263-X}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Elleray |first=D. Robert |title=A Millennium Encyclopaedia of Worthing History |publisher=Optimus Books |location=Worthing |year=1998 |isbn=0-9533132-0-4}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Hare |first=Chris |title=Historic Worthing: The Untold Story |publisher=The Windrush Press |location=Adlestrop |year=1991 |isbn=0-900075-91-0}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Nairn |first1=Ian |author1-link=Ian Nairn |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |author2-link=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Sussex |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |year=1965 |isbn=0-14-071028-0}}\n*{{Cite book |url= https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/Sussex/vol6/pt1/pp270-280 |title=A History of the County of Sussex: Volume 6 Part 1: Bramber Rape (Southern Part) |chapter=West Tarring |editor-last=Salzman |editor-first=L.F. |editor-link=Louis Francis Salzman |year=1980 |work=[[Victoria County History]] |publisher=British History Online |pages=81\u201392; 270\u2013280 |accessdate=9 October 2009}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Andrews Church, West Tarring}}\n[[Category:13th-century church buildings in England]]\n[[Category:13th-century churches in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Church of England church buildings in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in West Sussex|West Tarring, Saint Andrews Church]]\n[[Category:Churches in Worthing]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the other church in the Borough of Worthing dedicated to St Andrew|St Andrew's Church, Worthing}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox church\n|name                 = St Andrew's Church\n|image                = St Andrew's Church, West Tarring, Worthing.jpg\n|caption              = The church from the northwest\n|location             = Church Road, West Tarring, Worthing, West Sussex BN13 1HQ\n|country              = England\n|coordinates          = {{Coord|50.8247|-0.3958|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n|denomination         = [[Church of England]]\n|website              = [http://www.tarring.org.uk/st-andrews-west-tarring.org.uk/index.htm Saint Andrew's Parish Church, West Tarring]\n|founded date         = 11th century\n|founder              = [[Archbishop of Canterbury]]\n|dedication           = [[Saint Andrew]]\n|dedicated date       = By 1372\n|consecrated date     =\n|status               = [[Church of England parish church|Parish church]]\n|functional status    = Active\n|heritage designation = [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade II*]]\n|designated date      = 11 October 1949\n|architect            =\n|style                = [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]]\n|groundbreaking       =\n|completed date       =\n|construction cost    =\n|capacity             =\n|parish               = West Tarring, St Andrew\n|deanery              = [[Rural Deanery of Worthing]]\n|archdeaconry         = [[Archdeaconry of Chichester|Chichester]]\n|diocese              = [[Diocese of Chichester|Chichester]]\n|province             = [[Province of Canterbury|Canterbury]]\n|rector               = Rev. Mark Lyon\n}}\n\n'''St Andrew's Church''' is the [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Tarring, West Sussex]], [[England]]. Founded in the 11th century in a then rural parish which had earlier been granted to the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], the church remained a [[Royal Peculiar|peculier of Canterbury]] <!-- (sic) !--> for many centuries thereafter. It served nearby parishes when their churches fell into disrepair, [[John Selden]] was baptised here, and the church became a base for [[smuggling]]. The present building is mostly 13th-century, and its tall spire is a landmark in the area.<ref name=WAPH168>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1977|loc=\u00a7168.}}</ref> The church is a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade II* Listed Building]].\n\n==History==\nThe parish of West Tarring is now part of the Borough of Worthing, but has ancient origins as a [[South Downs]] [[strip parish]] of about {{convert|1200|acre|0}}.<ref name=VCH18267>{{harvnb|Salzman|1980|pp=270\u2013280.}}</ref>  It ran for about {{convert|3|mi|0}} from its northern extremity at Bost Hill, on the track to [[Findon, West Sussex|Findon]] (now the [[A24 road (England)|A24 road]]), to the [[English Channel]] coast in the south, and was much narrower apart from a thin strip of land extending westwards.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies12>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=12.}}</ref><ref name=DaviesFig3>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|loc=Fig. 3.}}</ref> Many coastal parishes in Sussex were this shape: many different soils and varieties of land would be included within the boundaries, from chalky downland in the north to marshy grassland near the coast.<ref name=Davies12/> Two settlements developed, of which West Tarring was the larger and more central. (The name \"Tarring\" was, and still is, also used, but the \"West\" prefix was often used to prevent confusion with [[Tarring Neville]] near [[Lewes]].)<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies5>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=5.}}</ref> [[Salvington]], the other settlement in the parish, is high on the slopes of the South Downs.<ref name=Davies12/>\n\nThe first documented description of West Tarring was in about AD 939, when [[Athelstan of England|King Athelstan]] granted the [[Manorialism|manor]] of Tarring to [[Canterbury Cathedral|Christ Church]] in [[Canterbury]] (now Canterbury Cathedral).<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies1>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=1.}}</ref> At the time of the [[Domesday Book]] in 1086 it was still held by the [[Archbishop of Canterbury|archbishop]] and had 41 inhabitants. A church is known to have existed at that time;<ref name=VCH18267/> it is likely to have been a wooden building.<ref name=Davies149>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=149.}}</ref>\n\nThe present [[flint]] and stone building<ref name=IoE302248>{{NHLE |num= 1354775 |desc=West Tarring Church (St Andrew's), Church Road (south side), Worthing, Worthing, West Sussex |year=2007 |accessdate=27 September 2009}}</ref> began to take shape in the mid-13th century.<ref name=Davies150>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=150.}}</ref> At that time, the [[Rector (ecclesiastical)|rector]], Simon of Tarring, provided sanctuary for [[Richard of Chichester|Richard of Wych (later St Richard of Chichester)]], the new [[Bishop of Chichester]].  He had been barred from his own palace there by [[Henry III of England|King Henry III]], who had been angered by the election of Richard as bishop in place of [[Robert Passelewe]].  While he was based at the church, Richard travelled throughout Sussex, taking services and reputedly performing miracles; he was [[Canonization|canonised]] in 1262.<ref name=Davies150/>\n\nThe dedication to [[Saint Andrew]] was first mentioned in 1372.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=MEWH48>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1998|p=48.}}</ref> In the 15th century the [[chancel]] and tower were rebuilt,<ref name=IoE302248/> apparently under the influence of Canterbury.<ref name=Nairn>{{Harvnb|Nairn|Pevsner|1965|pp=392\u2013393.}}</ref>  The [[rood screen]] also dates from that time.<ref name=VCH18267/> The church only had modest wealth \u2014 its internal fittings were valued at [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]6.13[[Shilling|s]].4[[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|d]]. (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|6.67|1561|r=-1}}}} as of {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} in 1561<ref name=\"Davies151\u2013152\">{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|pp=151\u2013152.}}</ref> \u2014 and unusual fundraising activities were popular.<ref name=VCH18267/> [[Parish Ale|Church ales]] \u2014 drinking sessions held in the church, at which the [[churchwarden]]s sold beer to raise funds for its upkeep \u2014 were popular throughout the 16th century,<ref name=VCH18267/> and often proved to be uproarious occasions at which large quantities of luxurious food were eaten and various entertainers performed.<ref name=Davies153>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=153.}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Organ (music)|organ]] was installed in the late 16th century.<ref name=Davies153/> Bells were hung in the tower by 1518, and there were five in 1533. These had been cast at the Tapsel (or Topsell) family's bell foundry near the church; the Tapsels cast many bells in West Tarring, for churches across Sussex, for about 200 years, and also invented the [[Tapsel gate]] used in some Sussex churchyards.<ref name=Davies155>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=155.}}</ref><ref name=SCM24>{{Cite journal |last=Roberts |first=William J. |year=1950 |title=Tapsel: his gate |journal=Sussex County Magazine |publisher=T.R. Beckett |location=Eastbourne |volume=24 |page=497 |url= http://scm.pastfinders.org/scm_24_tapsel.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070427215629/http://scm.pastfinders.org/scm_24_tapsel.htm |archivedate=27 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe nearby parishes of [[Durrington, West Sussex|Durrington]] and [[Heene]] had been linked to West Tarring since the [[Middle Ages]]. Their [[tithe]]s were combined, and they were administered for ecclesiastical purposes by the incumbents of St Andrew's:<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies149/> for example, burials and baptisms were carried out at West Tarring.<ref name=VCH18220>{{harvnb|Salzman|1980|pp=81\u201385}}</ref><ref name=VCH18221>{{harvnb|Salzman|1980|pp=85\u201392}}</ref> By the 17th century, in common with many churches in the area, Durrington and Heene's churches had declined and fallen into ruin. By 1680 both were in such poor condition that their parishioners were allowed to travel to worship at St Andrew's instead, and services were no longer held at Durrington or Heene.<ref name=VCH18220/><ref name=VCH18221/><ref name=\"Hare28\u201329\">{{Harvnb|Hare|1991|pp=28\u201329.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Lychgate at St Andrew's Church, West Tarring.jpg|thumb|right|The early 20th-century lychgate, with the spire of the church behind]]\nMajor changes were made in the mid-19th century. In 1845 the church ceased to be a peculier of Canterbury and instead was placed under the [[Diocese of Chichester]], in conformity with other Church of England churches in the area.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=MEWH48/> In 1853 the vicar instigated a [[Victorian restoration|restoration]] of the church, raising most of the \u00a32,200 (\u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|2200|1853|r=-2}}}} as of {{CURRENTISOYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} himself.<ref name=Davies157>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=157.}}</ref> Changes included the removal of the timber [[West gallery music|west gallery]],{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} the addition of a vestry, the stripping of previous interior alterations and a complete overhaul of the interior (although certain fittings were retained and reinstalled),<ref name=MEWH48/> and the replacement of the organ.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies157/> Also in 1853 Charles and George Mears<ref>{{cite web |url= http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=West+Tarring&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=WEST+TARRI |title=West Tarring S Andrew |last=Rix |first=Geoff |date=10 November 2006 |work=[[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]] |publisher=[[Central Council of Church Bell Ringers]] |accessdate=22 April 2013}}</ref> of the [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] recast four of the bells into a new [[Change ringing|ring]] of six.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies156>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=156.}}</ref> The restoration took seven months and was completed in time for [[Holy Week#Holy Week in Protestant churches|Holy Week]] 1854.<ref name=Davies157/> In 1885 [[mosaic]]s designed by the [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival architect]] [[William Butterfield]] were installed by Italian craftsmen in the aisles and around the tower arch.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/><ref name=Davies160>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=160.}}</ref>  The church roof partly collapsed around the same time and had to be repaired.<ref name=Davies160/> In the 20th century a [[lychgate]] was erected at the churchyard entrance, the [[reredos]] was replaced, the organ was replaced again, the roof of the chancel was renewed and some [[stained glass]] was added.<ref name=Davies160/><ref name=Davies159>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=159.}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Baptismal font|font]] was replaced with a [[Victorian era|Victorian]] one: the main section of its medieval predecessor was removed and taken to Australia by the [[Henty brothers|Henty family]] when they emigrated.<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies160/> The Hentys were successful farmers, especially of [[merino sheep]], and lived in one of West Tarring's largest houses. Thomas Henty, the patriarch, sent three of his sons and 150 sheep to [[Western Australia]] in 1829. Eventually the whole family moved to Australia: the pioneers settled in [[Tasmania]], while [[Edward Henty]], another son, became the first settler in [[Victoria, Australia|Victoria]] and was instrumental in developing the sheep-rearing industry there.<ref name=\"Davies143\u2013145\">{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|pp=143\u2013145.}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1977|loc=\u00a7166.}}</ref> They gave the font they had taken with them to a cathedral in Melbourne, which some sources state is [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Melbourne]]<ref name=Davies160/> while the Sussex Parish Churches website states this was at [[St Paul's Cathedral, Melbourne]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sussexparishchurches.org/content/view/594/33/ |title=Worthing \u2013 St Andrew, West Tarring |work=Sussex Parish Churches |date= |accessdate=}}</ref> the architect of which, [[William Butterfield]] had previously worked at St Andrew's Church.\n\n[[Smuggling]] was popular in the Worthing area between the early 18th and early 19th centuries \u2014 sometimes out of necessity, such as during a period of economic hardship in the 1820s which caused the developing town to stagnate.<ref name=Hare100>{{Harvnb|Hare|1991|p=100.}}</ref> One of the leading smugglers at that time, William Cowerson, was employed at St Andrew's Church on restoration work; he regularly used the [[Tomb|table tombs]] in the churchyard to store smuggled alcohol and other contraband.<ref name=Hare101>{{Harvnb|Hare|1991|p=101.}}</ref><ref name=Davies19>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=19.}}</ref>\n\n==Building==\nSt Andrew's Church is an [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] building with some [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular Gothic]] elements.<ref name=WAPH168/><ref name=IoE302248/>  It is a [[Knapping|knapped flint]] structure with stone dressings,<ref name=IoE302248/> and is relatively large in comparison with others in the area\u2014probably because of the influence of Canterbury.<ref name=MEWH48/><ref name=Nairn/>\n\nThe [[nave]] survives in its entirety from the 13th century. It has five [[Bay (architecture)|bays]] with aisles, a [[clerestory]], a vestry on the south side and porches on the north and south sides. The aisles and clerestory have [[lancet window]]s, and the whole composition is in the Early English style.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> The chancel and tower were rebuilt in the 15th century in the Perpendicular style, and the tall octagonal [[Roof shingle|shingled]] spire was added in the 16th century. The chancel has  Perpendicular-style windows with two lights; some of the tower windows more closely resemble the earlier [[English Gothic architecture#Decorated Gothic|Decorated Gothic]] style.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> The east window of the chancel is more ornate than usual: paired shorter lights flank a much taller central light which is surrounded at the top by sexfoils ([[hexafoil|six-lobed]] circular openings).<ref name=Nairn/> The tower and chancel have [[buttress]]es with quoins and dressings of [[ashlar]].<ref name=IoE302248/> The tower also has an interior stair-turret in one corner.<ref name=VCH18267/> Its west door, in the Perpendicular style with a [[hood mould]], is not original: it was inserted in the late 15th century. The windows above it have elaborate [[tracery]].<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> Paul Chapman of [[Hove]]-based [[stained glass]] designers [[Cox & Barnard]] made windows for the west ends of the north and south aisles. They were installed in 1958 and depict [[Thomas Becket|Saint Thomas of Canterbury]] and [[Richard of Chichester|Saint Richard of Chichester]] respectively.<ref name=SGR-22345>{{cite web |url= http://www.stainedglassrecords.org.uk/Ch.asp?ChId=22345 |title=Stained Glass Windows at St. Andrew, Tarring, Sussex |last=Eberhard |first=Robert |date=September 2011 |work=Stained Glass Records website |publisher=Robert Eberhard |accessdate=25 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nInside, there are five pointed arches on each side of the nave, with round columns topped by [[Capital (architecture)|capitals]]. The mosaic decoration, depicting the [[Apostle (Christian)|Twelve Apostles]], runs between and above them, and extends to the tower arch with its octagonal columns.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=Nairn/> The chancel arch was restored in the mid-19th century, but the 15th-century chancel screen was retained during the renovations of 1853. Also in the chancel are six [[misericord]]s, two with carved heads.<ref name=IoE302248/><ref name=MEWH48/><ref name=Nairn/><ref name=Davies159/>\n\nThere are several memorials in the church. The Henty family is commemorated by a tablet and a 19th-century window near the altar;<ref name=VCH18267/><ref name=Davies160/> there is also a window for [[Robert Southey]], the poet, who was the father-in-law of the vicar (Reverend J. Warter) who had restored the church in the mid-19th century.<ref name=Davies160/> The most famous man associated with St Andrew's Church, [[John Selden]],<ref name=Davies61>{{Harvnb|Davies|1990|p=61.}}</ref> was baptised here in 1584<ref name=WAPH168/><ref name=MEWH25>{{Harvnb|Elleray|1998|p=25.}}</ref> and has a memorial and a plaque.<ref name=MEWH48/>\n\n==The church today==\nSt Andrew's Parish Church has been a [[Listed building#Categories of listed building|Grade II* Listed Building]] since 11 October 1949.<ref name=IoE302248/> Such buildings are defined as being \"particularly important\" and \"of more than special interest\".<ref name=EH2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/caring/listing/listed-buildings/ |title=Listed Buildings |year=2010 |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |access-date=26 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DEarkz4v?url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/caring/listing/listed-buildings/ |archive-date=27 December 2012 |df= }}</ref> As of February 2001 it was one of eight Grade II* listed buildings in the borough of Worthing.<ref name=IoEStats-WSx>{{Cite web|title=Images of England \u2014 Statistics by County (West Sussex) |url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/StatisticsPage/default.aspx?StatsCounty=WEST%20SUSSEX |work=[[Images of England]] |publisher=[[English Heritage]] |year=2007 |access-date=2 January 2013 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DNVqdtdK?url=http://www.imagesofengland.org.uk/StatisticsPage/default.aspx?StatsCounty=WEST%20SUSSEX |archive-date=2 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nToday the ecclesiastical [http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parish.php?p=10/142 parish] is smaller than the ancient parish, but the northern part up to Salvington is retained. The other boundaries are the [[West Coastway Line|railway line]] to the south, The Boulevard in the west and a line west of Loxwood Avenue to the east.<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.achurchnearyou.com/parish.php?p=10/142|title=West Tarring Parish Church of S. Andrew |year=2009 |work=A Church Near You |publisher=[[Church of England]] |author=[[Archbishops' Council]] |accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of places of worship in Worthing]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Davies |first=Roger |title=Tarring: a Walk Through its History |publisher=Roger W. Davies |location=Tarring |year=1990 |isbn=0-9516309-0-3}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Elleray |first=D. Robert |title=Worthing: a Pictorial History |publisher=Phillimore & Co. |location=Chichester |year=1977 |isbn=0-85033-263-X}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Elleray |first=D. Robert |title=A Millennium Encyclopaedia of Worthing History |publisher=Optimus Books |location=Worthing |year=1998 |isbn=0-9533132-0-4}}\n*{{Cite book |last=Hare |first=Chris |title=Historic Worthing: The Untold Story |publisher=The Windrush Press |location=Adlestrop |year=1991 |isbn=0-900075-91-0}}\n*{{Cite book |last1=Nairn |first1=Ian |author1-link=Ian Nairn |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |author2-link=Nikolaus Pevsner |series=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides#Buildings of England|The Buildings of England]] |title=Sussex |publisher=[[Penguin Books]] |location=Harmondsworth |year=1965 |isbn=0-14-071028-0}}\n*{{Cite book |url= https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/Sussex/vol6/pt1/pp270-280 |title=A History of the County of Sussex: Volume 6 Part 1: Bramber Rape (Southern Part) |chapter=West Tarring |editor-last=Salzman |editor-first=L.F. |editor-link=Louis Francis Salzman |year=1980 |work=[[Victoria County History]] |publisher=British History Online |pages=81\u201392; 270\u2013280 |accessdate=9 October 2009}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Andrews Church, West Tarring}}\n[[Category:13th-century church buildings in England]]\n[[Category:13th-century churches in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Church of England church buildings in West Sussex]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed churches in West Sussex|West Tarring, Saint Andrews Church]]\n[[Category:Churches in Worthing]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Andrew%27s_Church,_West_Tarring"}
